ns1:Book06c54ca7-7c6e-43a3-9f4d-3cf934d6c26f a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Mariko Tamaki" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52989" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In this thoughtful story, expert plotting and pace are delivered through text and image. Quiet Rose and excitable Windy rekindle their summertime friendship with new interests, including horror movies, “boobs” and boys.\r
Tight dialogue, with captions and brief narrative sections in Rose’s voice, address the socioeconomic gap between visitors and local teens, as well as sexism and relationship dynamics. “‘You can’t get herpes from a flip-flop.’ ‘I think maybe you can.’” Rose observes the teens’ hook-up culture and the discord between her parents. In this story, there are no easy solutions. Drinking and unwanted pregnancy contrast with Mom’s sadness about her miscarriage.\r
Whether they be of smooth-cheeked children, spotty teens or worn adults, monotone illustrations depict characters of such individuation they seem sprung from real life. Double-page spreads revel in heady moments: swimming in dark waters, running through a thunderstorm, and watching the ever-fascinating teenage Dunc, as he pedals a bicycle along the path.\r
Another summer passes and this somewhat dark tale ends quietly, as it began. Like in life, everyone keeps rolling on. Images of the empty cottage echo with the sound of the ticking clock, as Rose contemplates what’s next: “Boobs would be cool.”""" ;
    ns1:name "This One Summer" ;
