    ns1:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Little_Brown ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Kid-centred language, illustrative fonts and dynamic images work to a theme that most children will recognize. “Have you seen Crankenstein? Oh, you would totally know if you had.” Whether he doesn’t want to wake up, or there isn’t enough syrup for his pancakes, or he has to go to school, “Crankenstein would say, ‘MEHHRRRR!!!’”\r
Rich, colourful images recall smooth, fuzzy airbrush effects. In one scene, a gloppy spoonful of shiny red cough syrup makes its way toward the green, twisting face of Crankenstein. (“Crankenstein hates gross cough syrup.”) Another shows the gaping mouth of a fellow Crankenstein at the playground. She holds her unicorn doll—head in one hand, body in the other. “MEHHRRRR!” she cries. Crankenstein watches from a distance, huddled over his own broken robot figurine: “MEH?” Whether being read to, or reading on their own, children will enjoy this lighthearted look at life’s fraught moments. They may even gain perspective on their own fits of frustration.\r
In the end, both Crankensteins are returned to a sunny state, playing ball together as a rainbow arcs over the playground. In the foreground, the unicorn stands repaired—with robot parts.""" ;
