    ns1:publisher ns1:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns1:reviewBody """This poem celebrates cats and their nocturnal life with a strong, sensuous start: “From the alley, music drifts. Shadows sway to a trumpet riff….”\r
The story begins with a single pair of dancers and builds as more and more cat-pairs gather through the night. From two to four to “Six cats tango in red capes, up and down the fire escapes,” all the way to “Twenty conga left and right, in splashy florals, plaids and stripes.” The strong rhythms beg to be read aloud. Short phrases and repetition encourages beginning readers.\r
Dark and moody illustrations feature brick, metal fixtures and the night lights of inner city landscapes. One delightful spread shows cats perched like birds on washing lines as irate people curse at them from dark windows. There is depth and sophistication in an image showing the cats stealing away, among the steel girders of a rail system, high above a lone taxi. Dawn begins to glow as the poem comes full circle with the first powerful lines, and then—it’s nighttime again!""" ;
