ns1:Book1debcff4-7602-4699-8c9f-626757fcc6d4 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Giovanna Zoboli" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55361" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Chronicle_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Whether delicately holding his tail while perched on the toilet, or selecting a tie for his natty suit, the crocodile protagonist of this wordless picture book is the epitome of old-world style and gentility. \r
\r
Story-dense images are rich in texture and atmosphere, using watercolour, coloured pencil and pastel-smudge effects. They are delightful to pore over, conveying the crocodile’s morning ablutions and breakfast in his cozy apartment, as well as his eventful commute through bustling streets and public transit. One sequence shows the subway, packed with individuated characters: a child in a tutu costume throws a tantrum; a giraffe’s scarf winds up its neck; the crocodile reads his paper, until crowds force his long jaw to point into the air. Another sequence shows him buying flowers and a packed lunch before hurrying through the gates of his workplace—the crocodile enclosure at the city zoo. Throughout the tale, there is much opportunity for storytelling, conjecture and prediction, along with fun read-aloud moments of eccentric noises: “tlin tlin,” jingle the crocodile’s keys as he leaves his apartment; “SBAM!” sounds the slamming door; “PEEEEEEE” squeals the traffic on the overpass; “WROOOOOOOMM” roars the streetcar as it whooshes past. The final sequence offers a humorous reverse to the beginning, as the crocodile meticulously undresses for work—to sprawl by his enclosure’s water feature, open jaws menacing the humans peering through the glass.""" ;
