    ns1:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:MacMilan ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In late 19th century China, little Bao is a young peasant boy captivated by the vibrant characters of Chinese opera and reverent of the local deities. When a foreign Christian priest smashes the village idols and demands they “Worship one god! One god only!” Bao becomes leader of the ‘Society of the Righteous and Harmonious Fists’. Practising rituals that allow the bandits to transform into powerful gods who believe themselves invulnerable to gunfire, they travel through northern China, slaughtering the “foreign devils.”\r
This historical graphic novel is a compelling mix of fact surrounding the “Boxer Rebellion” and fable that allows readers to get inside the psyche of the Chinese soldiers. A sepia-toned palette depicts drought and the grim reality of peasant life. Visuals erupt into vivid colours when the commoners transform into warrior gods in magic realism sequences. Clear dialogue carefully accompanies the strongly visual driven narrative: “Come brother disciples! Let’s make these devils bleed!”\r
Seduced by fear and hatred, these freedom fighters head toward Peking to liberate China from foreign influence. Themes of colonialism, religion and the ambiguity of moral certitude are strong throughout. Even as readers are drawn in by the passion and fervour of the soldiers, the extremes they go to become questionable, as little Bao is swept up in his cause and winning at all costs.""" ;
