ns1:Book3ace09b8-679d-4a67-865a-b1bfd5a8ff45 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Melanie Florence" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53611" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Clockwise_Press ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Told in the alternating voices of young Kateri, who is just starting school, and her disappeared Cree mother—her nimâmâ—who watches over her as a ghost, this moving tale addresses the issue of disappeared indigenous Canadian women in an age-appropriate manner. Looked after by her grandmother, Kateri is told trickster stories and taught beadwork and shawl dances, but she aches for her mother; her mother longs for her “little butterfly.” As we witness the milestones of Kateri’s life, from finding love to marriage and pregnancy, we watch over her alongside her mother, lending poignancy to a story that is both vivid and powerful.\r
Written in free verse, the voice of Kateri is strong and clear: “‘Tân’tê nimâmâ?’ I ask nôhkom.‘Where is my mother?’‘Lost,’ she says. Lost?‘If she is lost, let’s just go find her.’Nôhkom smooths my hair, soft and dark as a raven’s wing.‘She’s one of the lost women.’” Her mother replies in her ethereal voice, written in italics, even if her daughter cannot hear her: “My heart aches for her. My beautiful girl.I will always be your mother, Kateri.Even if I’m not there, sleeping, dreaming of you.”\r
Soft and sweeping mixed-media art uses both digital and hand-drawn techniques. With muted colours and layered imagery, there is a ghostly quality to an empty chair or a floating photograph from the past that resonates deeply.\r
A haunting story that in part uses magical realism to tell its potent tale. An afterword gives important context and background.""" ;
