ns1:Book415df776-4c0d-4b16-ae4d-39dabb2d21e7 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Matt de la Peña" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54286" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2018"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Penguin_Random_House ;
    ns1:reviewBody """There are as many forms of love as there are hearts to experience it and this picture book shows the affective range from fleeting instants to sweeping, inarticulable feeling. Parental love is the first and most fundamental, coming from “two wide-eyed figures standing near the foot of your bed.” Love can also be a song on a cab radio, the setting summer sun, “the made-up stories your uncles tell” and self-love. And love implies darker feelings, too, of loss and fear—the end of summer; “your family nervously huddled around the TV”; a vague, bleak dream of emptiness—as well as “love overlooked,” as when a parent “wakes at dawn and rides to work on the bus,” leaving an older sibling to make a breakfast of “burned toast that tastes like love.” Without editorializing or moralizing, this book expands poetically upon the “tiny beacons of light” of a complex emotion, always insisting on the presence of love and its centrality.\r
Realistic, textured and colourful, the illustrations depict each instance of love with a warmth and a familiarity that belie the absence of a straightforward narrative. The images laudably portray a range of scenes, contexts and ethnicities—a schoolgirl drops change into the guitar case of a “man in rags” busking outside a city subway station; a young girl in a hijab lies in a flowery field looking up at the sky; a father dances with his daughter on the roof of their trailer, surrounded by detritus as well as the gleam of a lake. Love and its permutations are multiple and moving.""" ;
