ns1:Book4470a11c-4413-4c7d-a3f7-794410936d1a a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Christopher Paul Curtis" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54850" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2007"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Scholastic ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Eleven-year-old Elijah Freeman is the first child born into freedom in Buxton, Canada, a settlement of African-American slaves who escaped the United States. When a conman steals money that Elijah’s friend has saved to buy his family’s freedom, Elijah, a naïve, “fra-gile” child heads into Michigan to stop him. He witnesses the horrors of slavery before courageously heading home. \r
\r
The story evolves slowly, allowing characters’ personalities, aided by realistic dialect, to show delightful humour, tenderness and shared suffering. “…people that use to be slaves are toting things ‘round with ‘em that caint be seen with your regular eyes.” The community itself takes a central role. Elijah reads a letter aloud, telling a woman that her husband has been whipped to death. “… once Ma and them women bunched up ‘round Mrs. Holton with their watching, waiting eyes and hands, it felt like a whole slew of soldiers was ringing that parlour with swords drawed and waren’t no sorrow so powerful it could bust through.” \r
\r
Descriptions of daily life, rock-fishing, pie baking and chores create a sense of safety covering deeper truths. “Maybe all the sad things ‘neath the scars and burns…of their kin were stories best not looked at too hard.” More graphic descriptions of slavery appear in the climax. Powerful themes work in beautiful synchronicity; these include the search for truth “You always got to look at things the way they is not the way you wish 'em to be, the struggle for freedom, wisdom through adversity and strength in community.""" ;
