ns1:Book468aeee4-d875-4adb-b427-2d77de7f7d1b a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Joanne Schwartz" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53827" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """A boy describes his life as a miner’s son in a Maritime village. In the morning, he stands at the window looking out at the ocean expanse while his father “is already deep down under the sea, digging for coal.” With each new activity, the boy thinks of his dad in the tunnels underground.\r
The illustrations, done in ink and watercolours, are both beautiful and haunting, oscillating between the father’s stark reality and the boy’s bright scenes of playing on the swings or walking by the sparkling sea. The mining scenes are almost completely black, with just two figures crouched in a sliver of light at the bottom, drilling in one, escaping a cloud of coal in another. Above ground—the sea stretches across two pages—darker brush strokes show gentle waves while white brush strokes show the sun’s blinding reflection. The boy appears at the bottom of the page. His features are rudimentary, composed of only a few simple lines.\r
The text is minimal, with only one or two lines on most pages, but often has a poetic feel: “The sun sets slowly, sinking into the sea.” The boy knows he will likely become a miner too: “I think about the bright days of summer and the dark tunnels underground. One day, it will be my turn.”\r
The author’s note explains the mining legacy that was a reality for boys from the late 1800s up until the 1950s, when the story takes place.""" ;
    ns1:name "Town Is by the Sea" ;
