ns1:Book4b79a638-da0c-4446-864d-d2144b75f555 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Emily Gravett" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53457" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2007"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:MacMilan ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Charming pencil sketches, collage effects, die-cuts and pullouts make this book a visual feast. Scrapbook-style spreads explore the myriad fears experienced by a sweet mouse, who marks up the pages with a bitten down pencil. Birds, cats and “what’s under the bed” are just some of the fears explored.\r
Anxious nerves are reflected in frantic layouts. One spread dramatically portrays the mouse’s fear of going down the sink drain, with a spiral of Polaroid photo images. At its centre, the drain is shown with the mouse’s tail emerging, clinging to the pencil for dear life.\r
Fun, brief language (“I get edgy near sharp knives”) competes with jokey, dense text incorporated into the illustrations (“my carving knife … three tails in my hand, and three mice running”). Page headings give the scientific term for each fear, such as “Clinophobia (Fear of going to bed)” and “Musophobia (Fear of mice).”\r
With a light, witty touch, the book urges the examination of our own fears. This message is underlined by the final image: a certificate of bravery, to be filled in by readers. “This is to certify that blank was very VERY brave about blank.”""" ;
    ns1:name "Little Mouse's Big Book of Fears" ;
