    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=54853" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher "Amulet"^^xsd:string ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Referencing fairy tales and gothic horror, this mystery-adventure features Irish orphans, 14-year-old Molly and her 10-year-old brother Kip, who take on work for a seemingly ghoulish family (the Windsors) on their desolate estate. \r
Eloquent language conjures a world of horse-drawn carts, market days, storytellers and supernatural beings: “A cold wind was now wuthering around her. The house groaned. The tree creaked. Leaves shuffled. She could almost see the icy currents sliding between the hills like living things… searching for prey.” \r
Dark suspense is balanced with the growing warmth between young servants Molly and Kip, and little Penny Windsor, her parents and even her selfish brother Alistair. Sly humour adds further entertainment: “spent the next day preparing to spy on the night man—a task that mostly involved steeling their nerves and ignoring their common sense.” \r
The chilling night-stalker and his not-so-giving tree depict the pitfalls of greed and indulgence. The story includes an action-packed climax, full of desperate moments, where the characters finally defeat spurious dreams and evil forces. “A story helps folks face the world, even when it frightens ‘em. And a lie does the opposite. It helps you hide.” In the end, the family is free to heal, while Molly and Kip begin their own new journey.""" ;
