    ns1:datePublished "2012"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In this clever modern-day morality tale, a little fish steals a hat from a big fish. He knows stealing is wrong, but that doesn’t stop him. Convinced he can get away with it, he nabs the hat while the big fish is sleeping.\r
The story unfolds from the point of view of the little fish. Readers will roar as he tries to justify his wrongdoing and reasons: “It was too small for him anyway. It fits me just right.” The little fish swims off, thinking he’ll be long gone by the time the big fish wakes up. “I am going where the plants grow big and tall and close together. It is very hard to see in there. Nobody will ever find me.”\r
Deep sepia tones with pale aqua and salmon accents are used to depict this underwater adventure in which stylish illustrations are rendered digitally and in Chinese ink. Text appears in a clean off-white bar of space above the illustrations or on the opposite page. The overall effect is slick, modern and minimalistic. With both the text and the illustrations, less is more here, with big ideas conveyed simply.\r
The last few panels of the book are wordless, the ending communicated solely through illustrations. As the big fish is seen swimming off with his hat, readers will giggle and draw their own conclusions.""" ;
