ns1:Book5a250b43-9a06-4b2c-ba33-620a668e751e a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Andrea Wang" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56646" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2021"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Neal_Porter_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In the family Pontiac, driving down a country road in the 1970s, Mom spots watercress, growing wild. They pull over. The parents used to eat watercress in China. So they commandeer the children’s aid, and soon the whole family is barefoot, wading in a muddy ditch to harvest the special treat. Humiliated, the girl hopes a passing car doesn’t recognize her. Her brother soaks her with the wet plants, covered in snails. She recalls past moments of shame: her hand-me-down clothing; her parents collecting old furnishings, put out on the road for the trash pick-up. At supper she refuses to eat the watercress, now cleaned and stir-fried in garlic oil. Then Mom shows her an old photograph of her family back in China, when she was a child. Mom reveals a painful memory, that the little boy in the picture—her brother—died during the Great Famine. A whole new perspective opens on her family, and the girl tastes the watercress. Everyone eats it all up, making a new family memory together. \r
“Mom’s eyes are as sharp as the tip of a dragon’s claw. Dad’s eyes grow wide. ‘Watercress!’ they exclaim, two voices heavy with memories.” \r
Sleek, poetic language conveys a tale of familial love and acceptance, layered with the memories of two generations: an Asian-American girl, growing up in rural Ohio (“A car passes by and I duck my head hoping it’s no one I know”), and her immigrant parents, living their cultural heritage in a new country: “From the depth of the trunk, they unearth a brown paper bag, rusty scissors, and a longing for China.” \r
The brief tale is packed with convincing details, evoking the family’s economic hardship (“old Pontiac,… faded by years of glinting Ohio sun, pelting rain, and biting snow”), cultural mores (“‘It is fresh,’ Dad says. ‘It is free,’ Mom says.”) and the protagonist’s intense emotions about it all: “dinner from a ditch.” \r
Realistic illustrations use watercolour effects to convey the stye and sprit of the ’70s—right down to the yellowing tints that recall old Kodak photos. One image features Mom’s hands—expertly rendered, down to the glossy finish on her nails—holding a sepia-toned family portrait: a family of four, wearing solemn frowns and utilitarian garb. The daughter’s ear-length hair and eyewear are reminiscent of Mom’s present-day hairstyle and glasses, as seen on the facing page. (“‘My little brother. Your uncle.’ We hold our breaths. Mom never told us what happened to him.”) A subsequent spread shows the girl holding the old photo, eyebrows tilting in a new expression of empathy. Mom’s figure stands behind the child, arm resting across the back of her chair—the very image of protector, sentinel and support. On the dinner table, the lush green dish of watercress is dappled with garlic buds. Dad is seated, his gaze intent on the girl, a strand of watercress poised on his chopsticks. (I look from my uncle’s hollow face to the watercress on the table and I am ashamed of being ashamed of my family.”) \r
The story beautifully resolves its messages about memory and intergenerational understanding, as the girl finally tries the watercress (‘bites me back with its spicy, peppery taste”), and by enjoying it together, the family adds a new and happy chapter to their history: “we eat it all and make a new memory of watercress.”""" ;
