ns1:Book6ba7dee6-8cd9-4d6f-85fa-36dd0f8f502a a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Issa Watanabe" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55687" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2020"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher "Gecko Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Forced migration, whether driven by natural disaster, political violence, endemic poverty or any other reason, is fraught, difficult, stressful and disheartening. Migrants is a wordless picture book that chronicles the journey of a group of migrants, presented as anthropomorphic animals. The animals must leave their home and journey together, carrying babies and bundles, huddling close as they trek and cook and try to sleep. A pale humanoid character, suggestive of Death, follows the animals, often astride a blue ibis, a bird that in many cultures represents the communication between life and death. Eventually, the animals reach a body of water and pile into a simple, open, wooden boat that lurches over the dark waves… and spills the migrants into the sea. One of the migrants, a rabbit, dies in the crossing, and the other animals gather to mourn. Finally, after travels that feel increasingly demoralizing, the animals reach a flowering tree, and a little rabbit girl stands before it, her paws open to its pink blossoms: hope standing before hope. The picture book is a powerful call to empathy. The topic is sad, and the book doesn’t sugar-coat the frightening realities of forced migration. But the despair is countered by the animals’ resilience, and by the sense of community and togetherness that gives them the strength to continue. \r
\r
The two-page spreads all have a dark background: the sky is a deep indigo or black, the trees are outlined in grey, and the ground and the waves are hatched in dark greens and blues. Inspired by photographs of migrant children sleeping, the gloom of the forest emphasizes the bright, vibrant colours and complex textures of the animal. The use of colour against dark backgrounds evokes the continued ray of hope during difficult times. The drawings are intricately detailed—one shows a fallen tin cup, another a pair of small white hands reaching out of the water, another the tired wrinkles of an elderly rhinoceros—as if the care evident in the creation of the book were a tribute to the migrants themselves.""" ;
