ns1:Book76b66c49-a9c7-4673-b3fb-71ddffd4459d a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Neil Gaiman" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53207" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2008"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:HarperCollins ;
    ns1:reviewBody """As a toddler, “Nobody Owens” (“Bod” for short) wanders into an old English graveyard following the senseless murder of his family. The tiny orphan is adopted by ghosts and given “freedom of the graveyard,” allowing him to fade and see in the dark. Through a series of otherworldly adventures, Bod manages to uncover his true identity and overcome the mysterious forces that are set on destroying him.\r
Bod grows up in the graveyard; each episodic chapter finds him several years older, until at 15 he is ready to go out into the world of the living and “leave no path untaken.” Themes of self-discovery, overcoming adversity and living life to the fullest are at the heart of this riveting read.\r
This feat of fantasy storytelling is rich with allegory, magic and adventure. Moving between the worlds of the living and the dead, Bod meets the Indigo Man, uncovers the grave of the Sleer and falls through the Ghoul-Gate into a dreadful underworld. His guardian, Silas, seems to be neither dead nor alive, but a bridge between two worlds.\r
Richly imaginative, the language is atmospheric, with its gorgeous descriptions of place, character and emotional states: “The air was alive with birdsong and bee hum.” and “He stepped out of the shadows, detaching from them like a patch of darkness.”\r
Black and white ink-brush illustration, peppered throughout, add to the eerie and mysterious world that is so masterfully woven.""" ;
