ns1:Book7d8b1056-7b2c-4a26-a7c9-1be48202ccb1 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Martine Leavitt" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53350" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Seventeen-year-old Calvin has just realized how much he has in common with the titular character of the Bill Watterson comic strip. There’s his name, of course; plus, as a child, he had a stuffed tiger named Hobbes. Recently, Hobbes has been talking to Calvin all the time. Calvin also hears his classmate Susie, even when she’s not there. \r
\r
Calvin has just been diagnosed with schizophrenia. This novel is a long letter to Watterson, who Calvin is convinced can make his voices go away if the author will only write one more comic strip. And so Calvin, Susie (who may or may not be there in body), and of course the delusion of Hobbes set off across the frozen expanse of Lake Erie to find Calvin’s saviour. \r
\r
The first-person perspective is unusual. The speaker also sees himself as part of a cast of several interlocutors, and many sections present them rather as characters in a play. The shifts in perspective are moving, as the reader must enter Calvin’s reality, instead of the other way round, as is usually the case when those suffering from mental illness must interact in neurotypical situations.""" ;
