    ns1:datePublished "1981"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Inspired by a Canadian folk singersongwriter and his song “Northwest Passage,” this book offers a stimulating, artistic approach to Canadian history.\r
Intriguing lyrics (“Seeking gold and glory, leaving weathered, broken bones, and a long forgotten, lonely cairn of stones”) lead readers through Canadian exploration history, using a timeline, maps and information-rich captions.\r
The genius of the book is in the exclusive use of original illustration. Wild Canadian landscapes and portraits of historic figures alike are rendered in a loose painterly style that’s rich in detail, colour and symbol. In offering a brilliant example of artistic engagement with non-fiction, this book may inspire similar projects among young students of history.\r
An author’s note introduces the book. Complete song lyrics and music are reproduced at the back. “A Gallery of Explorers” provides thumbnail images and brief biographies of key historic personalities. A selected bibliography also suggests age-appropriate resources for further reading. This book is a must for any library of Canadian culture.""" ;
