ns1:Book85f6b369-cae1-4412-9782-65b15ff59b9a a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "William Grill" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53438" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher "Nobrow Press"^^xsd:string ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In 1916-1917, Ernest Shackleton made his unsuccessful expedition to the South Pole. The story—from the intensive preparations to their last-ditch rush for rescue—is covered in 32 brief chapters.\r
Quaint and evocative imagery makes this non-fiction picture book unique. Colour-pencil forms and figures are stylized—soft-edged, yet graphic and precise—for an effect that is both retro and highly sophisticated.\r
Large-format pages make text blocks appear small and easily read, like captions. Neutral-toned language allows dramatic facts to shine alone: “Exhausted, the men clung together for warmth as snow fell silently, covering them like a white blanket.” Themes of cooperation, perseverance and hope reverberate, as wild gales and crushing ice test the expedition team.\r
The interrelation of text and image aids comprehension and elevates artistry. The chapter titled “The March” comprises a lone paragraph and shows a file of men, dogs and equipment traversing the vast blankness of the page. Other pages show detailed illustrations of supplies and sled dogs, and there’s even a spread showcasing the entire crew. Readers can dip into sections, following their own interests, although by the final chapters of this harrowing tale, they’ll be reading every word.""" ;
    ns1:name "Shackleton's Journey" ;
