    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Red_Deer_Press ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Many perspectives contribute to create a compelling picture of life on a tobacco plantation just prior to the US Civil War. Brief free verse chapters skillfully convey the differentiated voices of Phoebe, cook Bea, brothers Shad and Will, as well as Master, his daughter Tessa and an unusual “Birdman” from up north.\r
The injustice of slavery is vividly portrayed. The language shows various ways the characters manage, from outright rebellion to wily survival within the system. \r
Phoebe’s protests take the form of muteness and teaching herself to read—a serious crime for a slave. Her journey from fear to strength is reflected in the healing process of a bird she rescues. \r
“I never told Shad,But I dreamed it too.After Momma left.On those dark nightsWhen I reached for herAnd felt as cold and emptyas the straw beside me,I believed in Will’s Canada.”\r
Courage, history and the power of poetry are beautifully interwoven in this thoroughly enjoyable book.""" ;
