    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Simply_Read_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """As a little bluebird seeks the wind to help her fly, inventive language offers a wealth of metaphors for its presence: “tickling the grass.” “dancing with brightly colored balloons,” “making wishes” on dandelion puffs.\r
Delicate, large illustrations use a range of techniques—woodblock effects, collage and compositional blank space—to create whimsical images that play with perspective (bird’s-eye views.) As the bird searches for the wind in the park, one spread shows her among yellow-umbrella dandelions and an exquisite variety of dandelions gone to seed. The bird’s blue, spindly legs mimic the long green stems around her. In the distance, a narrow landscape creeps up along the side of the page, showing her own tree with its nest.\r
The bird flits from place to place in scenes both panoramic (a busy market from high above) and intimate (a cozy home seen through a windowpane). Meanwhile, the story’s message of capacity and independence slyly unveils: “How could she ever fly without her friend’s help?” In the end, the bird realizes she is perched high atop the city’s clock tower—where she also finds the wind: “It must have been resting there, watching her fly.” The final spread shows the bird soaring high above a detailed scene of her park, ringed by the busy city.""" ;
