ns1:Book9c4d8522-3631-4f2a-a6e2-bf5b51fca04d a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Nicola I. Campbell" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52610" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2008"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Groundwood_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """This is Shin-chi’s first year going away to an Indian Residential School, so he brings a keepsake from home: “He held the tiny canoe safely in his hands. The sweet scent of cedar smelled just like his dad.” In simple but evocative language, the story conveys Shin-chi and his sister’s journey through beloved traditional lands to the harsh environment of the school.\r
Stylized illustrations use strong line and soft textures to depict the shorn hair of the schoolchildren, the bleakness of the dorm and mess hall. Soft-focus photographic effects convey the warmth of the land, as Shin-chi sneaks away to launch his tiny canoe on the river, sending it home.\r
The message of survival and resistance is clear: Shin-chi makes a friend (“Little mischief times two,”) and cleaves to his family’s values (“‘I’m checking to see if the sockeye salmon are here’ … ‘Not yet my Shin-chi, but they will come’”). In the end, the siblings are joyfully reunited with their family for the summer break: “They found their dad carving them their very own dugout canoe.”\r
An introduction gives more information and perspective on Indian Residential Schools, in youth-friendly language.""" ;
