    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Darcy is the adolescent author of a manuscript, Afterworlds. The book has been accepted for publication, and now, postponing college, Darcy must deal with the fast-paced literary scene. The interleaved chapters are the book-within-the-book: Afterworlds is the story of Lizzie, who dies briefly after a terrorist attack, and after coming back to life, finds out that she’s able to will herself in and out of the hereafter. With the help of a cute guide named Yamaraj, she learns to negotiate the afterlife, with all its shadows and perils, and befriends a lost ghost who follows her into the world of the living.\r
\r
Darcy’s world is full of the stress of final edits, the whirlwind life of book promotion, and balancing a new romance with the glamour of the literati of New York City. The parallel, internal chapters, the pages of which are marked with black bands, like minor keys on a piano, are a more narratively straightforward, albeit paranormal, love story. The two protagonists are complete opposites: Darcy comes across as slightly superficial, while Lizzie is a brave adventurer. The parallel novels raise questions about reality and experience, and about authorial voice and character development, as well as alluding to some of the ins and outs of the publishing industry.""" ;
