ns1:Bookb580691c-da9c-450c-9c51-01aaf079055b a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Suzy Lee" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=56179" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Chronicle_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """A little lone skater creates gorgeous swirls on otherwise blank pages. As her turns and spins become increasingly difficult, her sketchy form smudges and multiplies . . . until the omniscient artist crumples the paper and rebuilds a new world for her. A well-used rink emerges; another child appears. Eventually the little skater is playing simple ice games with dozens of other children on a pond in the countryside. With stunning skill, the art of drawing line and movement is demonstrated in this wordless story, conveying a theme of transition—from lonely perfection to homey companionship. \r
The title page hints at the virtuosity of images to come, as the author’s name and book title are represented by a single, flowing pencil line. Subsequent images use the same quality of line to trace the path of a loosely sketched little figure skater (in red mittens and pom-pom hat) and her smudgy shadow. As her figures become more complex, the line qualities begin to vary: a brush stroke, a broken line. One image shows a bird’s-eye view of the skater spinning, as concentric and overlapping circles radiate from her twirling form: her red mittens create crayon trails; rubbed-out shadows of arms, legs and her pom-pom hat recall the path of her turns. Further images play with composition and page space; they grow more filled-in and messier, working with shading, erasure and discordant lines, as the skater stumbles, and finally wipes out (hat flying). \r
The artistic process, with all its frustrations and requisite determination, is cleverly addressed with a realistic sketch of crumpled paper, followed by the same page, smoothed out—on which the little skater sits, staring at her fallen hat. A cozy message of fun and companionship is built before readers’ eyes, as another child joins the picture—smiling as she lands on her butt. The little skater lies back to watch a dog slip across the ice, as other children appear—everyone sliding with their whole bodies, not using their blades at all. Touches of greens, browns, yellow and pink, are introduced as the rink accommodates more skaters: an older child pulls a young one, using a scarf; two girls chat and lounge on the ice; snowballs fly across the page-gutter, and much more. When everyone gathers into a skate conga-line, the idea of community is complete. \r
Sketches on the endpapers also address artistic process, while showing a great range of expression and detail. At the front is a near photo-realistic sketch of a pencil and eraser, bordered by a simple line—the blank page. At the back, the artist’s tools are worn to nubs, while stacks of drawings can be seen peeking from underneath a finished landscape sketch of the story’s pond. Crumpled paper, pencil and eraser shavings litter the edges. Altogether this book is a feat of artistic prowess and storytelling.""" ;
