ns1:Bookb8a4751c-8789-4cdc-9375-d69394b5cba4 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Amy Reed" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53961" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Told from the perspectives of three very different young women, this tale about recognizing and addressing violence against women, in its obvious and its more insidious forms. Additional voices offer the myriad perspectives of fellow-students and townsfolk, as everyone struggles under the lie of an unaddressed gang-rape of a high school freshman, by members of the football team.\r
The characters are skillfully drawn, with compelling back stories and punchy dialogue. Grace’s liberal religious beliefs offer a spiritual slant on a wholly dispiriting situation; sexism is ingrained in the family culture of punk-queer Rosina; brilliant Erin is on the autism spectrum.\r
Open and supportive discussion among women is highlighted, and the need for personal activism is underlined as authority figures—teachers, police and some parents—are shown to be overly invested in the status quo.\r
The book’s great strength is its portrayal of the breadth of sexist culture and its oppressive effects on everyone, not just the most obvious victims. Allies among the boys at school and parents at home provide balance and reprieve. Related issues such as socio-economic inequity and racism are artfully incorporated into plot and dialogue “You do know that people out here are just waiting to shoot people like me, right? Hello? I’m brown and gay.”\r
In the end, the girls succeed in their aims most satisfyingly—even as the story questions our legal system: “What punishment is equal to those boys’ crime, equivalent to the permanence of what they did? Is there even such a thing as justice?”\r
A resource list of support organizations is included.""" ;
