ns1:Bookc5ad08ff-01be-4e11-901c-c8ad13e184fb a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Grahame Baker-Smith" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52077" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2010"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns1:reviewBody """On the cover of this book, the title is written as FArTHER—a hint at its dual theme of father, as leader and example, and the future generations that make further progress.\r
The illustrations depict an almost surreal world, in which a colossal father in overalls builds wings and flying machines. Objects, animals and textures are depicted in a hyper-realistic manner, while human faces are rendered as smooth as marble carvings. The effect supports the parable-like nature of the tale.\r
This nostalgic, reflective story uses poetic language to engage young readers. Rich, metaphoric vocabulary describes the father’s house: “It was made of stone and slate and fastened deep into the cliff. It was safe and rooted in the rock. But inside, my father dreamed of air and flight.” This book provides opportunities for discussions about children’s hopes and dreams, just as it encourages speculation about the adults in their lives.\r
The conflict between the father’s preoccupation and the son wanting his attention is beautifully described by the language and illustrations. It is only after the father is gone and the boy has grown that he finds himself drawn to the same dream. When, in the final image, the grown son’s new baby reaches toward the moon, it echoes the book’s stirring message: a father’s solid foundation offers his child a chance to fly.""" ;
    ns1:name "Farther" ;
