ns1:Bookcb25fb98-b692-4b32-8620-ab53e386625a a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Jason Reynolds" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53956" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In this powerful verse novel, the visceral and heartbreaking nature of gun violence among inner city youth is explored with depth, craft and heart. When Will witnesses his older brother, Shawn, being shot dead, he decides to follow “the rules.” No crying, no snitching and take revenge: kill the perpetrator who killed the person you love.\r
This unflinching work then moves into a compressed and alternate reality where Will spends one minute and over 200 pages descending seven floors in an elevator with a gun in his back pocket. At each level he meets a new ghost, one who has met a similar fate to his brother’s: his first girlfriend, his Uncle Mark, even his father.\r
Told from the point of view of 15-year-old Will, the poems are raw, with straightforward language that packs a punch. “I never held a gun. Never eventouched one.Heavier thanI expected,like holding a newbornexcept I knew the cry wouldbe muchmuch muchmuch louder.” There is a relentless rhythm to the book that builds tension and emotional impact.\r
A visual poem, shaped as a question mark and made up of the repeated word “Why,” a list poem with alternate names for a gun, several anagrams (“feel = flee”) and the creative use of line breaks and white space make for an even more engaging read.\r
The futility of gun violence and gang culture is driven home through the highly personal lens of a young man struggling to come to terms with grief, anger and numbness.""" ;
    ns1:name "Long Way Down" ;
