ns1:Bookd0e01714-30f3-4c50-9a24-028c070842df a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Nicola Yoon" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53105" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher "Doubleday Canada"^^xsd:string ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Maddy’s always had time on her hands—247 living in her “white balloon.” Now she’s grown into a thoughtful and observant 18-year-old, devoted to books, her distance-learning projects and her mother.\r
Much of Maddy’s communication with the outside world is made up of instant messaging dialogues, emails and sticky notes. Illustration and design also contribute to the storytelling, through images of book pages, humorous charts and graphs, Madeline’s personal word definitions and her “Life is Short™ Spoiler Reviews” on Tumblr. The result is a breezy yet brainy approach that offsets the intensity of a life-threatening first love.\r
Olly, a sexy parkour enthusiast, is the opposite of Maddy and her quiet ways. Their relationship is portrayed with an idealized glow—in contrast to the violence in Olly’s home and the severe restrictions on Madeline’s existence. Maddy writes: “sus•pi•cion … The truth you don’t believe, can’t believe, won’t believe.”\r
Underlying these dramatic circumstances are the values of reaching out, taking risks and getting hurt in the great, wide world. Madeline’s decision to leave her bubble results in physical danger, the loss of profound illusions and finally—for the first time in her life—the gift of self-determination.""" ;
