    ns1:datePublished "2013"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:MacMilan ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In this picture-book bestiary, Little Mouse presents some fearsome beasts in poetic style. A lion, a shark, a bear and an owl, among others, are all framed by the book’s rhyming explanations (“This crab … Was made to grab”) with, as counterpoint, Little Mouse’s consonant addenda (“Wasps worry me”). The descriptions of the animals are playful but rooted in fact. For instance, we learn that “Some snakes kill with poisonBut the Boa-ConstrictorSeizesThen squeeeeezes,Then swallows ‘em whole.”\r
\r
The full-page colour illustrations feature Little Mouse interacting with the drawings—painting through and across pages, drawing hearts, mice or fish, adding messages like “I do not want to be crunched by a crocodile.” The otherwise artfully representative drawings of the animals are augmented by whimsical collaged additions, such as a toothbrush and toothpaste for the crocodile, an image of a shoe on the rhinoceros, and newspaper clippings (the bear page has an advertisement for a ‘middle-sized chair’: “Eaten too much porridge? Finding that little stool just a touch too tiddly?”) \r
\r
For additional fun, many pages have three-dimensional alterations—tears, chomps, glued-on mouse-made scrapbook art and flaps.""" ;
