    ns1:datePublished "2017"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:MacMilan ;
    ns1:reviewBody """In this nearly wordless story, a little girl in a red parka gets lost in a snowstorm on her way home from school. At the same time, a wolf pack is on the move and its youngest member gets left behind in the whiteout. When the two strays find each other, the girl follows the howls of the cub’s family to take him home. She collapses from the strain and the wolf pack calls out until her dog and mother are able to rescue her.\r
A testament to the power of visual storytelling, the only words used are the sounds of the girl (“huff, huff), her dog (“bark! bark!”), the cub (“whine, whine”), his pack (“hooowwwlll”) and other animals they encounter along the way.\r
Artwork in pen, ink and watercolour provides the emotional arch of the story. In a sketchy, cartoon style, the textures of the storm and landscapes that stretch over double-page spreads bring the reader into the intensity of the situation. The expressiveness of the little girl’s eyes and body language convey enormous emotion—fear, cold, apprehension, terror and exhaustion.\r
Sweeping illustrations that go to the edge of the pages also provide a sense of immersion in the story. Large bubbles are sometimes used to separate the girl’s and the cub’s stories, lending perspective.\r
A heroine’s journey about wildness, resilience, family and what it means to truly help.""" ;
