ns1:Booke2115451-9b73-4d68-b465-058e0279c7ab a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Julie Flett" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55838" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2019"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Greystone_Kids ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Seasonal episodes recount the story of young Katherena’s move to the countryside with Mom and her trusty dog, Ôhô (meaning ‘owl’ in Cree). There she befriends the neighbour, Agnes, an elderly potter. The pair enjoy their common interest in art (Katherena loves to draw) and nature, until Agnes becomes bedridden. With the help of Agnes’s grown daughter, Katherena decorates Agnes’s room with all the drawings inspired by their seasons together. \r
\r
The passage of seasons combines with the passage of a friendship, in this gentle tale about two artists—one still a child and one near the end of life: “‘Visit me again Katherena!’ Agnes says with a smile. I smile back and give her a big wave. I can’t wait to go home and start drawing.” The theme of change runs through the plot: “It’s a mucky spring morning as we pack up the last of our belongings and leave our little home in the city by the sea,” as Katherena adjusts to new surroundings, “But I don’t feel like drawing. \r
\r
My hands are cold.” She makes a new friend—who will also soon depart: “It’s getting cold and windy and creaky. Agnes says she’s getting creaky too.” \r
\r
Spare compositions use muted colours and soft, textural effects, creating outdoor and home scenes. One image shows the little family at Agnes’s kitchen counter, “She likes salmon stew.” Ôhô the dog is strategically underfoot as Katherena helps cook, and steam rises from the great cast-iron pot. The next image is a blustery double-page spread in snowy tones, as Katherena returns to her own house. Red cardinals (seen also through the kitchen window in the previous spread) perch in the bare tree branches. Ôhô is neck-deep in the drifts; Katherena clutches snowdrop bulbs—a thank you gift from Agnes. \r
\r
Throughout each episode—spring, summer, fall, winter, then spring again—language and images are imbued with nature, “I help by gathering extra leaves that’ll get mixed into the soil. The worms love this,” as the story touches on Indigenous knowledge: “I tell her about Cree seasons. This month is called pimihâwipîsim—the migrating moon.” Readers may be inspired to learn more about the different Cree moons and their meanings. \r
\r
A bittersweet ending offers opportunities for discussions ranging from the passing of seasons to the passing of family elders: “I leave with an ache in my heart, but I’m so glad to know my friend Agnes.”""" ;
    ns1:name "Birdsong" ;
