    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:HarperCollins ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Structured as a meta-narrative, this tale about the real bear that inspired the character of Winnie-the-Pooh is told here as a bedtime story by a mother to her young son, Cole: Harry Colebourn is working as a vet during World War I when he rescues a bear cub from a trapper. He names her Winnipeg, after his hometown. Winnie becomes “the Mascot of the Second Canadian Infantry Brigade,” but when the regiment ships out, Harry must bring Winnie to “the Big City,” reminding her sadly, “I’ll always love you. You’ll always be my bear.” At the London Zoo, Winnie is eventually visited by a young boy, Christopher Robin, who becomes smitten with the bear, and whose father, Alan Alexander Milne, goes on to write storybooks about the friendship between a little boy and a bear. As the story closes, we learn that the author is the great-granddaughter of Harry Colebourn, after whom her son, Cole, is named. The text jumps back and forth between the early 20th-century and the contemporary narratives, with Cole’s italicized questions innocently interrupting the bedtime story.\r
\r
Full-page and framed watercolours provide soft, realistic renditions of the scenes—the soldier coming across the leashed bear at the train station, Winnie riding shotgun on the way to London, Christopher Robin gazing at his still-unnamed teddy bear. Soft and realistic, the illustrations also occasionally provide an aerial perspective—of the Valcartier base, or the London Zoo—and the muted colours lend an air of time past to the paintings""" ;
