    ns1:datePublished "2006"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Simon___Schuster ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Rabbit borrows a book from his public library and begins to read. From this moment, the words of this story are attributed to the book he is reading—one about wolves. The language relates ordinary facts about wolves: “They have sharp claws… and dense fur.” Meanwhile, the illustrations depict increasingly dramatic and threatening scenarios, with wolves leaving the pages and Rabbit becoming ever more entangled in the wolfish elements under discussion.\r
Simple illustrations in sketchy, charcoal-textured line with a subtle use of colour are enhanced by a strong, stunning layout. The theme of getting lost in a good book is beautifully depicted, as Rabbit goes ever deeper into a world of wolves waist deep in its fur, walking along its nose.\r
Young readers will appreciate nifty production tricks in this pretend library book, such as an old-fashioned date-stamp card that may be removed from its pocket, and an envelope containing a late return notice. Puns and wordplay up the ante on the story’s subtle humour. Readers of all ages will be surprised—even shocked—when Rabbit is devoured by the wolf at the end of the book. This ending, though, is softened by a humorous note: “no rabbits were eaten during the making of this book” and an alternative happy ending.""" ;
