ns1:Bookf1f801b3-1320-4235-ac74-c1edbfa34812 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Jenny Offill" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=55591" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2014"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Schwartz___Wade_Books ;
    ns1:reviewBody """Clever language conveys the experience of pet ownership through the voice of a little girl whose mother allows her “any pet you want as long as it doesn’t need to be walked, bathed or fed.” With the help of a resourceful librarian, “Mrs. Kinklebaum (who knows everything in the world),” the girl orders herself a sloth. \r
Charming illustrations in pen and watercolour effects depict expressive scenes between “Sparky” the sloth and the wispy-haired girl: watching him sleep in his tree, carrying him like an oversized and extremely floppy infant, and more. One spot image shows her executing a high kick as Sparky gazes elsewhere: “We played Kung Fu Fighter and I won.” In the next image, the girl stands upright; the sloth’s expression and position remain unchanged: “We played Statue and Sparky was very, very, good.” When neighbour Mary Potts (“Most Likely to Chew Close-Mouthed in Lunchroom,” “Excellence in Permission-Slip compliance,” “Best Fire Drill Liner-Upper”) challenges the sloth’s value as a pet (“My parrot knows twenty words, including God and ice cream”), Sparky is given intensive trick-training. \r
After Sparky’s lacklustre performance, notions of acceptance and understanding are emphasized as the illustrations grow rosy with evening light: “I reached over and tagged him on his claw.” The final image shows girl and sloth, sitting in the tree, gazing together at the setting sun: “You’re it, Sparky,” I said. And for a long, long time, he was.”""" ;
    ns1:name "Sparky!" ;
    pbs:isCoupDeCoeur false ;
