ns1:Bookf28aaf2c-e1a8-4fb5-a854-6c22bcbcbfa7 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Carson Ellis" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=53221" ;
    ns1:datePublished "2015"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Candlewick_Press ;
    ns1:reviewBody """“Home is a house in the country,” this picture book opens, then adds a assortment of other structures than can be homes too: an urban apartment, a raccoon den, even an overturned teapot. \r
Scant text takes the form of a list: “Clean homes. Messy homes. Tall homes. Short homes.” The few words also make playful use of internal rhyme: “Sea homes. Bee homes. Hollow tree homes.”\r
The illustrations use folksy colours and stylized doll-like figures to people the range of possible homes. A young girl sits at the window of a brick-walled apartment building dotted with cats, plants and mugs, with water towers and smokestacks defining the skyline; a bearded Norse god stands proudly in front of his home full of geometrical windows and flags. Some homes are partnered: the “underground lair,” a kind of Ali Baba’s cavern full of gold and treasure, lies right beneath a palatial home. Drawings feature lovely details, including such minutiae as striped orange stockings clothes-pinned to the rigging of a huge sailing ship (“Some homes are boats”), or a goose chatting up a pigeon from her nest atop the chimney of a messy home.\r
Wigwams, trailers, moon modules, nests: the variety is fascinating to contemplate and leads naturally to the author’s question: “Where is your home?Where are you?”""" ;
