ns1:Bookfb0e1621-6e22-4362-ac0e-aec3c1066b58 a ns1:Book ;
    ns1:author "Sheryl McFarlane" ;
    pbs:constellationLink "https://constellations.education.gouv.qc.ca/index.php?p=il&lo=52825" ;
    ns1:datePublished "1991"^^xsd:gYear ;
    ns1:publisher ns1:Orca ;
    ns1:reviewBody """This quiet book leaves readers rapt with rich descriptions of place and lifestyle. Using pristine language and telling detail, this somewhat lengthy story begins with an old man’s whale-watching, beach-combing, gardening and forest-gathering activities.\r
On the arrival of his daughter and her baby, the old man’s life expands to include others. As the baby grew, “She stuck to her grandfather like glue. And although he grumbled, he took her everywhere.”\r
Detailed, realistic illustrations depict beachscapes and the great forest. Painted boards of the house, porch and outdoor armchair provide backdrops for the small family at home. In one image, the girl sits on a moss-covered log while the old man teaches her which plants are good for gathering. In another, she plants seeds in the garden by herself. The mother comforts: “Your grandfather’s spirit has gone to leap and swim with the whales.”\r
The theme of passing on tradition and the renewal of life is encapsulated in the final scene, as the girl watches the whales the following summer and notices a little calf swimming with the pod: “a fierce cry of joy escaped her … she flew up the hill to tell her mother.”""" ;
